er English spy inspires a Quaker boy to run away from home. Three Philadelphia gentlemen conduct a romance through diaries and letters in the 1780s. Flighty teenager Charles Brockden Brown metamorphoses into a horror novelist by treating his friends as his literary guinea pigs. Emerson exchanges glances with a Harvard classmate but sacrifices his crush on the altar of literature--a decision Margaret Fuller invites him to reconsider two decades later. Throughout this engaging book, Crain demonstrates the many ways in which the struggle to commit feelings to paper informed the shape and texture of American literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx1783-1850. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican literaturexMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey1783-1850xHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmitié masculine dans la littérature. 0aAmitié masculinexHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aHommes dans la littérature. 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critiquex1783-1850. 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critiquex19e siècle. 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critique. 0aMale friendship in literature. 0aMale friendshipxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMale friendshipzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMen in literature. 0aSympathie dans la littérature. 0aSympathy in literature. 0aÉcrits d'hommes américainsxHistoire et critique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.c